What used to be one of the last casual local spots to get dinner at in the West Loop has recently rebranded itself as John Barleycorn circa 2010. My husband and I live 2 blocks from here and have been regularly coming for weeknight dinners, as well as entertaining friends and family during the week. Tonight we were surprised to come in at 6p, at which time they turned the lights down and turned up a playlist so loud that we could barely hear each other from across a 2 top. Now, I’m not opposed to loud music at a bar, but at 6p on a Tuesday I expect to at least be able to communicate to the person across from me. We asked the waitress what was up, and apparently they are “catering to a younger crowd”. Upon looking at the crowd, it appeared to be the same local and after work crowd it always has been so we continued to be confused. She informed us that they have started to do this every night, except for Mondays and on game days, including a DJ on Friday/Saturday nights. Apparently we are not the first to complain about this, but I guess are not concerned with keeping their local customers. Since they are about the only place in the West Loop with ample TV’s for game watching, we will be sticking to game days and move our week night dinners elsewhere. I suggest that if you want to be able to hear your fellow diners, and not listen to music that hasn’t been heard outside of Wrigleyville in 10 years then you do the same.

Gather round children for a textbook example of how careless “sports bar” staff can sour an otherwise perfect football Sunday. You see, yesterday was a huge day, for the Eagles last hope to clinch a playoff spot required a Bears victory over the Vikings. This created a rare and unique fan concept where I could cheer for the Bears along with most of my friends. “Let’s go to Green Street Local” they said. “It’ll be great fun” they said.  Arriving a full 45 minutes before kickoff, there were four TVs at the upstairs bar we were sitting at. They were set to DAL-DAL-DAL-CLE.  After talking to other people at our bar we all agreed that it should be CHI-KC-PHL-CHI. We had Bears, Eagles, and Chiefs fans, and we wanted everyone to have a decent view of their game based on position at the bar. It was fair and everyone would be happy.  After like 30 minutes of asking, their first “attempt” ended up with KC-PHL-CHI-CLE. This is how we enjoyed kickoff.  After another 30 mins of complaining, their second “attempt” ended up with KC-CHI-PHL-CLE.  Finally after like another whole hour of this BS they switched again this time to KC-PHL-CHI-CHI around half time. This is how it remained the rest of the game. Because of this, almost nobody at the bar had a good view of the game they wanted to watch. And nobody was watching the Browns!!!  To top it all off, our main bartender kept giving us rude gestures and curt responses when we repeatedly asked (politely and soberly) for the correct channels. I don’t think she was even listening to our team choices because even after the TVs kept changing to the wrong ones, she would point up and say “but they switched!?” and then ignore us. Maybe she was having a bad day, you can never know, but it certainly wasn’t helping the situation. I guess Step 1 would be don’t hire people who hate sports at your sports bar.  Thankfully, victory was ours in the end, but I won’t be returning here for any important games. They just don’t care about their supposed target market. That being said the food and drinks are good and the place is otherwise clean, open and modern. Probably great if you aren’t watching a game.
